## The Key Statement

> "A point from A in each punctured neighbourhood means **infinitely many** points from A in each punctured neighbourhood"

### What does this mean?

If even **one** point from A exists near x₀ in every zone you draw — then actually **infinitely many** points exist there.

**Why?** Because if there's one point x₁ near x₀, draw a smaller zone. Now there must be another point x₂ inside that smaller zone. Draw even smaller — another point x₃. This never stops. So you always get infinitely many.

---

## Reading the Number Line

The diagram shows x₀ at the center with points from A approaching it:

**From the right:** x₁, x₂, x₃ getting closer and closer to x₀

**From the left:** x₄, x₅ getting closer and closer to x₀

These points never reach x₀ but keep squeezing in from both sides — **infinitely many of them.**

---

## The Yellow Box — The Big Conclusion

```
lim xₙ = x₀,   xₙ ∈ A for all n ∈ N
n→∞
```

This says you can build a **sequence** x₁, x₂, x₃, x₄ ... of points from A that converges to x₀.

This is the connection between:
- **Accumulation points** (geometry — points clustering near x₀)
- **Sequences and limits** (algebra — a sequence approaching x₀)

They are **the same idea** expressed two different ways.

---

## The Final Line

> "Each accumulation point can be approximated arbitrarily closely by points from A"

This is the most human way to say it:

| Concept | Plain meaning |
|---|---|
| x₀ is accumulation point | Points from A get as close to x₀ as you want |
| Punctured neighbourhood | A zone around x₀ excluding x₀ itself |
| Infinitely many points | The approximation never runs out of points |
| lim xₙ = x₀ | The sequence of nearby points converges to x₀ |

